      {
         "id": "SECTION_prerequisites",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><span id=\"htZoomImageMsg\"></span></p><p><span id=\"htChartMsg\"></span></p><p><span id=\"htAmericaAbyaYalaMsg\"></span> (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "160fb48c-1711-491e-a1aa-e1257e7889af",
                     "text": "Porto-Gonçalves, Carlos Walter",
                     "page": "pp. 39-43",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text continues the teachings on how to add negative numbers and represent them. Therefore, we suggest studying the previous text (<htcite0>) before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1d69a491-3e55-4eec-abee-70374df66efc",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Modulating (Part I)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_Introdction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen adding negative numbers, we observe that we perform the calculations in the same way as when we add positive numbers. As a consequence, we can understand that sums, in this scenario, are like walking along a path such as the Peabirú in America (*Abya Yala*) (**Figure 1**) (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1d69a491-3e55-4eec-abee-70374df66efc",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Modulating (Part I)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/Mapswire/world-physical-map-graticules-mercator-v1_Peabiru.jpg\" id=\"imgPeabiru\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPeabiru', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Representation of the Peabirú path followed by Aleixo Garcia. © Mapswire (<htcite0>). Shared under the <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license.</a></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc",
                     "text": "Mapswire",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The fact that we walk in the same way, regardless of direction, brings another analogy already used in *History Tracers*, but this time related to the act of performing the same operation repeatedly, that is, multiplying (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Multiplying There as Here</b><br /><br />Multiplication is the repeated addition of numbers (<htcite0>). Can we say that we multiply to the left as we do to the right, with the difference that we keep negative signs on the left?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the Same Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_remembering",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Remembering\n\nLet us remember the conclusions we had related to the multiplication of positive numbers before taking the first steps toward negative numbers.\n\n#### The sum\n\nFirst, we saw that, when taking 10 steps to the right, we could represent those steps as follows (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the same numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"center_notation\"><math display=\"block\"><mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Sum of all ten steps taken to the right.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### A new representation\n\nIn the same text, we also saw that we could rewrite the successive sum of values as follows (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Adding the same numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"center_notation\"><math display=\"block\"> <munderover> <mo>∑</mo> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> </munderover> <mi>1</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>10 × (1)</mi>  <mo>=</mo> <mi>10</mi></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Sum of all steps.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Tabulating\n\nAs we continued our studies, we saw that, since certain results are common, we can write them in table form using the formula (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Understanding the Multiplication Table (0 and 1)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"><mi>N</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Result of multiplying by one.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "By using **Formula 1**, we learned that we arrived at the following table, which we named the **1 Times Table** (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Understanding the Multiplication Table (0 and 1)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent1\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "And finally, we learned that we can draw a graph with the numbers we multiply (<htcite0>) and, if we connect the points, we can obtain the drawing of a straight line (**Graph 1**) :",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6428e19-afcf-4d3b-916d-46e5a332ef53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Understanding the Multiplication Table (0 and 1)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart4\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 1</b>: Points of the 1 times table connected, forming a straight line. Graph made with the <htcite0> library.</div></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_mirror",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiplying to the left\n\nThe process of performing multiplications to the left is exactly the same as we remember. This means we will repeat numbers the same number of times, but because we are moving in the opposite direction, we will use the negative sign. To make this comparison clearer, we will rewrite the same steps performed for positive numbers, now for negative numbers.\n\n#### The sum\n\nSince we are walking to the left, we add negative numbers:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"center_notation\"><math display=\"block\"><mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>+</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>-10</mi> </math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 3</b>: Sum of all ten steps taken to the left.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### A new representation\n\nJust as we represented consecutive sums to the right, we can also represent them to the left:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"center_notation\"><math display=\"block\"> <munderover> <mo>∑</mo> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>10</mn></mrow> </munderover> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>10 × (-1)</mi>  <mo>=</mo> <mi>-10</mi></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 4</b>: Sum of all steps to the left.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Notice that in **Calculation 4**, although the number of steps is positive (10), since we are walking to the left, we keep the negative sign to indicate our direction.\n\n#### Tabulating\n\nTo write the multiplication table, we will make a small modification to **Formula 1**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"><mi>-N</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>-1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 2</b>: Result of multiplication by -1.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "When using **Formula 2** to create a multiplication table, we must not forget to add the negative sign to the result, indicating the direction we are walking:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent2\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: What about the graph?</b><br /><br />We saw that the negative sign indicates we are going in the opposite direction. What happens when we multiply by negative numbers?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Looking at **Graph 1**, we observe that as we move away from zero to the right, the result also moves away from the horizontal line in the upward direction. Since we continue adding repeated numbers when multiplying by negative numbers, we must again move away from the horizontal line; however, we will do so in the opposite direction to that of positive numbers, that is, downward.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart5\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Points from the -1 multiplication table connected, forming a straight line. Graph made with the <htcite0> license.</div></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Entendmos a multiplicação como somas repetidas do mesmo número?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "A multilpicação e soma estão ligadas, sendo a multiplicação entendida como somas repetidas da mesma quantidade."
      }
   ],
